{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14055"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14055"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.02,0.06,0.48,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14055"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3740"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing fatigue. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as an engineer and denies any recent changes in his diet or lifestyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale but otherwise well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are no other significant examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (130-170)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean cell volume: 76 fL (80-100)\u003Cbr /\u003EFerritin: 25 \u00b5g/L (30-300)\u003Cbr /\u003ETransferrin saturation: 10% (20-50)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecal occult blood test","CT abdomen and pelvis","Haemoglobin electrophoresis","Gastroscopy and colonoscopy","Bone marrow biopsy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with fatigue and laboratory findings consistent with iron deficiency anaemia (IDA). In a middle-aged man with IDA, the most appropriate next step of the available options is a semi-urgent endoscopic investigation via gastroscopy and colonoscopy. This is crucial to investigate the gastrointestinal tract for potential sources of occult bleeding, from sources such as peptic ulcers, inflammation, colonic polyps, or malignancies. Occult bleeding is a common cause of IDA in adults, particularly in men and postmenopausal women. This patient should also have coeliac serology and a urine test performed to exclude other important causes of iron deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal occult blood test\u003C/strong\u003E (FOBT) is not appropriate in this context given the patient\u0027s IDA. FOBTs are used to screen for colorectal malignancy in asymptomatic patients through the detection of microscopic blood loss. A positive or negative FOBT would still necessitate further investigation in a male patient with established IDA. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate investigation for IDA in this context. It is less sensitive than endoscopic procedures for detecting early mucosal lesions that could be causing chronic blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate investigation in this context. While it can help identify haemoglobinopathies such as thalassaemia which can lead to a microcytic anaemia, this patient has iron deficiency as a cause which must be further investigated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that is not routinely performed as a first-line investigation for IDA. It may be considered if the cause of anaemia remains unclear after less invasive investigations have been performed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopy investigation should be undertaken in men and postmenopausal women with  iron deficiency anaemia to rule out gastrointestinal bleeding."],"references":["GESA. 2022. Iron deficiency clinical update for general practitioners and physicians. Available at: https://www.gesa.org.au/public/13/files/Education%20%26%20Resources/Clinical%20Practice%20Resources/Iron%20Deficiency/Iron%20Deficiency%20Clinical%20Update%202022%20APPROVED.pdf","Snook, J., Bhala, N., Beales, I. L. P., Cannings, D., Kightley, C., Logan, R. P., Pritchard, D. M., Sidhu, R., Surgenor, S., Thomas, W., Verma, A. M., \u0026 Goddard, A. F. (2021). British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines for the management of iron deficiency anaemia in adults. Gut, 70(11), 2030\u20132051. Available at: https://gut.bmj.com/content/70/11/2030"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14055"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T10:52:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T11:00:45+09:30"},"relations